  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jeremiah 5:30-31. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 5:30-31",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "A wonderful and horrible thing is committed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— So stupendous a crime, that it is beyond the apprehension of man to conceive, much more to express, its greatness; and so abominable, that a man ought even to loathe the thoughts of it. What this is, we have in the next verse; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in the land ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, this land, which aggravates the greatness of the wonder that such a thing should exist in such a land! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The prophets prophesy falsely, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — Both priests and prophets agree to speak pleasing things to the people, thereby to keep up their interest and authority with them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And my people love to have it so ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— They are well enough pleased to be thus misled. If the prophets and priests will let them alone in their sins, they will give them no disturbance in theirs. They love to be held and governed by a loose rein, and like those rulers very well that will not restrain their lusts, and those teachers that will not reprove them: see note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 30:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And what will ye do in the end thereof ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And what can this end in, but a total corruption of manners? The consequence of which must be the utter ruin of the state. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "5:19-31 Unhumbled hearts are ready to charge God with being unjust in their afflictions. But they may read their sin in their punishment. If men will inquire wherefore the Lord doeth hard things unto them, let them think of their sins. The restless waves obeyed the Divine decree, that they should not pass the sandy shores, which were as much a restraint as lofty mountains; but they burst all restraints of God's law, and were wholly gone into wickedness. Neither did they consider their interest. While the Lord, year after year, reserves to us the appointed weeks of harvest, men live on his bounty; yet they transgress against him. Sin deprives us of God's blessings; it makes the heaven as brass, and the earth as iron. Certainly the things of this world are not the best things; and we are not to think, that, because evil men prosper, God allows their practices. Though sentence against evil works is not executed speedily, it will be executed. Shall I not visit for these things? This speaks the certainty and the necessity of God's judgments. Let those who walk in bad ways consider that an end will come, and there will be bitterness in the latter end.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
